[With wild unwelcoming hippopotami I have difficulty in understanding how one can diagnose anthrax in a live wild hippo. I suspect that they have 45 carcasses but only were able to confirm anthrax in 32. And "browsing" is eating leaves and such from bushes or low lying branches of trees. To acquire spores from soil they would have to be grazing, which hippos are known to do. As animals are drawn to salt, it would not be unexpected if some of the later cases got infected by licking blood extravasated from prior anthrax carcasses. While it is tempting to say that some animals will have been exposed to bacillus vegetative cells in the water, the survival of these cells in water is limited to a few hours.

The report does not specify the mode of official carcass disposal. Burning them, the optimum choice, would soon present difficulties in gathering enough firewood and fuel. So it is possible that the carcasses were buried, also not without problems. - Mod.MHJ


A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5334849,63183.]
